A: You can prevent the ProgressDialog from dismissing while screen orientation changes by checking if the ProgressDialog is currently showing before attempting to dismiss it.
Here's how you can modify your code:
public void prepareViews(int ID, boolean state){
    switch(ID){
    case USERNAME_TEXTBOX:
        LoginUsernameTextBox.setEnabled(state);
        break;
    case PASSWORD_TEXTBOX:
        LoginPasswordTextBox.setEnabled(state);
        break;
    case LOGIN_BUTTON:
        LoginButton.setEnabled(state);
        break;
    case LOGIN_PROGRESSBAR:
        if(state == true){
            LoginProgressBar.setVisibility(View.VISIBLE);
            LoginProgressBar.setIndeterminate(true); }
        else{
            LoginProgressBar.setVisibility(View.GONE);
        }
        break;
    case CONNECTING_DIALOG:
        if(state == true){
            if (progressDialog == null || !progressDialog.isShowing()) {
                progressDialog = ProgressDialog.show(MainActivity.this, "", "Connecting", true);
            }
        } else {
            if (progressDialog != null && progressDialog.isShowing()) {
                progressDialog.dismiss();
            }
        }
        break;
    }
}

In this modified code, before dismissing the ProgressDialog, we first check if the ProgressDialog is currently showing. If it is, we dismiss it. If it's not, we do nothing and prevent the app from crashing.

A: You can use onConfigurationChanged() method to handle the orientation changes.
@Override
public void onConfigurationChanged(Configuration newConfig) {
    super.onConfigurationChanged(newConfig);

    // Checks the orientation of the screen
    if (newConfig.orientation == Configuration.ORIENTATION_LANDSCAPE) {
        // Handle landscape mode
    } else if (newConfig.orientation == Configuration.ORIENTATION_PORTRAIT){
        // Handle portrait mode
    }
}

In this method, you can manage the behavior of your ProgressDialog according to the orientation of the screen.

